{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"D\n    \n      Train in Python → Export model.json + weights → Node-RED loads files (Recommended)\n      Train LSTM and PPO in Python (TF/Keras for LSTM, Stable-Baselines3/PyTorch for PPO policy). Export each to TFJS format: lstm/model.json + lstm.weights.bin, policy/model.json + policy.weights.bin, scaler.json (normalization params). The Node-RED custom node loads all three at startup — no Python process needed at runtime. For continual learning: Node-RED logs real experience to a file; a background Python script re-trains periodically and overwrites the exported files; Node-RED hot-reloads the new weights.\n      \n        Pros\n          No Python process running alongside Node-RED\n          Self-contained Node-RED node — just drop in the files\n          Best of both worlds: Python training ergonomics + JS runtime\n          MPC = random shooting in TFJS (works perfectly with discrete fan/heater)\n          Online learning via scheduled Python retrain → hot-reload in Node-RED\n          Each exported artifact is inspectable and replaceable independently\n        \n        Cons\n          Learning happens in batches (e.g. every 24h), not step-by-step\n          PyTorch PPO policy → ONNX → TFJS conversion adds one extra export step","choice":"d","id":null,"timestamp":1781070279068}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"A\n    \n      PyTorch throughout + Python HTTP server\n      LSTM + PPO in PyTorch. A small Flask/FastAPI server stays alive. Node-RED sends sensor data → Python runs MPC + PPO → returns fan/heater command. Python process does online learning step-by-step from each real observation.\n      \n        Pros\n          True step-by-step online learning\n          SB3 PPO is the easiest RL library available\n        \n        Cons\n          Python process must stay running — if it crashes, Node-RED goes blind\n          More moving parts to manage in production","choice":"a","id":null,"timestamp":1781070364498}
